review_title: Pretty decent for a small light
reviews: Its a pretty decent flashlight for just how small it is, but one problem i had was the light i received was pretty clearly used. Spots around where the pocket clip were where the finish on the light was worn off, and the pad that was supposed to be between the end of the battery and the end cap of the flashlight was already removed. Im gonna keep it but this really is not acceptable buying a new item no matter how cheap it is.

The Fox Anso Zero. Nice and light, unique blade style which offers lots of belly which makes cutting tasks easy. N690 steel, Plastic handles, and 2 hand open on this puppy. The pocket clip works great, and will be carrying more.

The Mcusta Tsuchi is a fairly decent pocket knife. Pretty light, Nice and sharp vg10 damascus blade with hammer marks looks real slick. Aluminum Handles make it nice and light. The only thing I'm not crazy about is the pocket clip, and the fact that it ships out tip town. Other then those nitpicks its a keeper. Definitely check out some Mcusta if you are into Knives. Got the yellow one which has a blue pivot and thumb stud. Looks pretty cool. :D

Got sent the wrong knife initially. It was a J A Henckel fine edge pro in a global 8" chef knife box hah. Sent that back and got the right one this time around thankfully. That being said its a nice upgrade for most people from the cheaper henckels and some of the starter victorinox and such. Nice and thin on the edge for some fine cutting. I have spent lots of money on cheaper knives in the past, and here's my advice.... just get the more expensive knives if you can. I mean you can get like 6 Fine edge pros for 1 of these but let me tell you on the 500th time sharpening a fine edge you will be ready to throw in the towel . Its a good knife and you still aren't dedicating twice the price for a top of the line chef knife.

review_title: Do you have a knife addiction? This was the answer for mine
reviews: Waited a long time to buy this and finally did it. Really sweet little knife. Smaller then i thought but still has a decent length on the blade itself. Amazing grip and seems fairly light, but obviously not as light as the volcano grip handles. Nice grippy texture on the G10 and sleek straight blade in S30V. The top of the blade is nice and thick which gives your thumb a nice ramp if that is how you chose t grip the knife. No real gimping but it still feels great and plenty of grip with the handles already. Uses the compression lock same as the Paramilitary 2. The spyder hole is partially covered by the handle but still accessible which has not been a problem for me. My only complaint is that i which i could get this knife blacked out.

reviews: Most people who buy alot of knives and people who buy alot of emersons will know that $220 is a really good price for an emerson. Also no skulls are printed on this knife which is a bonus if you are using it for work. There is a steel insert on the titanium frame lock to avoid sticking.

This knife i picked up locally and can say its a pretty handy little sucker. Its quite heavy for its size but feels good in the hand. The handle is a bit short for some people but you can choke up over the stud for a little extra milage if you feel it necessary. The blade itself sharpens up quickly on the ol sharp maker. The autolawks takes a bit of getting used to for most of us versed in the 1 handed liner lock close. Also should mention for people picky about their flippers the particular one i have requires wrist action to fully flip open. gets about half way or a little more open without assistance. For me not a big deal. The pocket clip is way too tight gotta loosen that up. Nice cutting edge and fairly thick blade stock for a folder.

review_title: Columbia River Knife and Tool (CRKT) 7460 BT-70 Folding Razor Edge
reviews: this is a big ol knife. Looks really unique. The blade was not sharp out of the box which is a negative for any knife. You will notice right away that thumb stud is really hard to get to. Its actually easier to just grab the end of the blade und pull the knife out. And for reference it is easier to use a nail knick then the thumb stud on this knife. You know what would make sense is a flipper stud or an emerson opener as there is lots of unused steel on spine of the blade. It is cool looking and probably the thickest grip on any folder i own including some of the larger cold steel knives width wise. Also not sure if it was intentional but the grind is not centered on this blade. I mean its still gonna work but for $96.76 i expect better quality control. The knife maker who came up with the design is great and i have no beef with Bob Terzuola but the quality control at the factory seems poor on this one. Coming from a customer who was very happy with the cheaper priced Fossil which is a great option i would suggest instead. Also the listed price now is 159.65 so if you are absolutely wanting this knife for the design like myself wait for a price drop.

Seems like a solid knife, and is my second in this series of which my first which was the resilience. the fit and finish is decent only noticed a bit of the blackening was rubbed off near the top of the handle, and the blade did not come to what is known to most people as factory sharp. Those are minor things though and that being said is a decent knife. Got it sharp and a lack of coating on the top of the steel liner won't stop the knife from functioning properly. I noticed some people knocking the spydercos made in china and i can honestly say that if you don't want to be spending a lot of money on spydies then support the chinese blades. In the sharpening department the 8cr13mov is really easy to get a solid edge compared to vg10 or zdp so don't be shy about buying a cheaper option.. Should also mention i use this knife in the kitchen quite a bit as well as a carry some of the time, and is pretty much a tiny chefs knife. Works great for mostly anything you might need to prep if you want a quick go to knife and don't want to go digging around for a kitchen knife. Haven't had any problems with rust so far. The pocket clip comes tip down which to some people is a problem but there is a 4 way option. Buy it!

reviews: I like it. Adjustable grip which is what i needed. The squeeze versions were not strong enough to hold the strings on my guitar and would cause buzzing. This capo gets the job done. Nuff said.

review_title: This knife is so sweet. Really great feel and look
reviews: This knife is so sweet. Really great feel and look. Used this knife to baton wood and really hammered the spine of the blade. Held up quite well considering the beating i put it through. Keep in mind you can still mess up your blade so don't get too hardcore. The black coating on the newer cold steel knives seems to hold up much better then the old school paint coating on the aus8a models. The g10 handles are grippalicious and to be honest i don't use the pocket clip on any of my cold steel knives as they are terrible. Other then that the blade shape is really handy the knife is bang on sharp, and after abusing the knife all day i ran it on the sharp maker really quick and seemed to get an edge back quite quickly. Its a larger carry option but great for if you need something around the yard or if you are hiking. Its nice to know you can have a folder that you can baton with in a pinch.

Not a bad overall knife. If you are worried about weight the i would recommend the Fiberglass Reinforced Nylon version as this one has some heft. The handle itself though seems to me much thinner then the FRN handle. Has a finger choil! Also has the jimping on the top of the knife near the handle and where the choil is like on the Paramilitary 2, but not as agressive. The entire knife has been blackened which i like alot even on the inside of the handle. Although i dont think the coating is as durable as on the PM2, thats what you get with this cheaper line of spydies so im not upset about it. Solid knife for the price, and again if you are worried about the weight i think there is the G10 handle with skelotonized liners and FRN versions. The knife opening is really tight on this knife and requires some working in. I had a hard time opening it with one hand right out of the box, but the knife locks up solid and really isnt a problem for me. Its a really cool knife considering its basically a cost efficient endura4. I would love to see the next endura series with the choil and choil jimping. Some people don't like the chisel grind but i prefer it with the serrations. I have a boker with serrations where the blade part is not chisel and it makes it really annoying to sharpen. Its actually better if the whole blade is chisel.

review_title: ... into the wave feature but the knife itself is easy to sharpen
reviews: im not sure I'm into the wave feature but the knife itself is easy to sharpen, and quite small. The pocket clip is really super tight which means i was just carrying right in my pocket. Although the knife is quite small it probably weighs about as much as a rat model 1. Grips are medium aggression g10 and the knife functions about as well as you would expect for the low price point. Not really sharp out of the box but has an edge. The steel is 8cr 13mov which most people will recognize as a mid grade steel. Really a actual treat how quick it sharpens up.

review_title: Spyderco Manix2 FRN Translucent Blue Plainedge C101PBL2
reviews: Probably the lightest knife you will ever own. Its so light you can forget you have it on you. If you own other spyderco knives the first thing you will think is man this does not feel as durable as the Resilience, or the paramilitary 2. Don't let this fool you, carry this thing around for a day or 2 and you are going to notice right away that it will be able to preform the tasks you need. The pocket clip is pretty much perfect not too tight. Considering most people arent going to be out in the woods with this knife batoning wood it should be almost perfect for every day tasks.
